    <title>Non-Zero Sum Games</title>



<p>We now introduce a famous thought experiment to push beyond the world of Zero-Sum Games. Instead of payouts, we now consider the utility to each player. For example, if someone plays a lottery, losing it may be worth <m>-1</m> utility, and winning might be worth <m>1000</m> utility, but winning or losing the lottery does not affect the other players playing it.
</p>

<p> <term>von Neumann and Morgenstern's Lottery:</term>  
Suppose that Rose has two possible outcomes in a lottery, <m>X</m> with utility <m>0</m> and <m>Z</m> with utility <m>10</m>. </p>

<question> 
<ol>
  <li> Determine the expected utility of the lottery for Rose if the probability of <m>X</m> is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> and the probability of <m>Z</m> is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.</li>
  <li> Determine the expected utility of the lottery for Rose if the probability of <m>X</m> is <m>p</m> and the probability of <m>Z</m> is <m>1-p</m>.</li>
  <li> Now suppose a third option exists, <m>Y</m> such that Rose's preferences are <m>X LESSTHAN Y LESSTHAN Z</m> (that is, it has some value between <m>0</m> and <m>10</m>). 
  Morgenstern and von Neumann propose that there is some <m>p</m> so that if <m>X</m> happens with probability <m>p</m> and <m>Z</m> happens with probability <m>1-p</m> so that <m>Y</m> has the same value as the lottery of <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>. 
  Determine (as a function of <m>p</m>) the value of <m>Y</m>.</li>
</ol>
</question>

<question> <term>Dating Dilemma</term>:
Suppose Rose and Colin have started dating and they are texting to decide what to do this evening. Colin would like to go to the basketball game <m>B</m> and Rose would like to watch a film <m>F</m>. Colin is irresponsible and didn't charge his phone, so it dies before a decision is made, but they both know the two options. They both value time apart as <m>0</m> utility, time together as <m>1</m> utility at the event they didn't suggest, and <m>2</m> utility for being together at the event they suggested.
</question>

<ol>
  <li> Make a game matrix for the dating dilemma. </li>
  <li> Determine what the players might do under rational play. (Assuming no further communication.) </li>
</ol>


<definition>
<term>Volunteer's Dilemma</term>:
Rose and Colin have been a mostly happy couple for some time now, but they disagree about who will do the dishes. Each has the option of either volunteering (V) to do the dishes or staying silent (S). Below is the payoff matrix (with S before V in rows and columns):

<md>
<mrow>\begin{bmatrix} (-10,-10) \amp (0,-1) </mrow>
<mrow>(-1,0) \amp (0,0) \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
</md>
</definition>

<p> Each player's best outcome is by staying silent, but that can also lead to the worst outcome. This dynamic is common enough that the aboriginal people of Tierra del Fuego have a word for it. </p>

<definition>
<term>Mamihlapinatapai</term> is the situation when two people are staring at one another, each hoping the other will volunteer to do something both want done but neither wants to do.
</definition>

<question> What should the Rose and Colin do assuming rational play? </question>


<p> A <term>movement diagram</term> is a matrix with arrows to demonstrate how players are incentivized to move in given situations. For example the prisoner's dilemma's payoff matrix is:
<md>
<mrow>\begin{bmatrix} (-1,-1) \amp (-10,0) </mrow>
<mrow>(0, -10) \amp (-5, -5) \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>The movement diagram should encapsulate that if a player <m>A</m> does not rat on player <m>B</m>, then <m>B</m> is incentivized to rat on <m>A</m>, and if player <m>A</m> suspects that player <m>B</m> will rat, they are incentivized to rat, demonstrated as below:</p>


