<p>NASH'S THEOREM</p>



<p>Now that we have seen that all classical games have a Nash Equilibrium (that is, a steady state) we want to analyze how to find them. We can do this, at least in small cases by recognizing what the Nash Equilibrium says!</p>

<p>A Nash Equilibrium guarantees that there is a pair of strategies so that neither players has an incentive to change strategy.</p>

<p>We will call a strategy for Colin <m>\textbf{q}</m> a <term>best response</term> to a strategy for Rose, <m>\textbf{p}</m>, if Rose has no incentive to change her strategy if Colin continues to play <m>\textbf{q}</m>.</p>


