<p>We will now formalize slightly more the difference between the types of stability in equilibria that we saw with Hawks vs Doves, and X vs Y.</p>

<definition>[Symmetric Game]
A game matrix <m>A</m> is said to be <term>symmetric</term> if <m>A</m> satisfies that Rose's entry in position <m>(i,j)</m> is always the same as Colin's entry in position <m>(j,i)</m>.  
(For those who have seen linear algebra, this means that if <m>R</m> and <m>C</m> are Rose and Colin's payout matrices, we have that <m>R^T = C</m>.)
</definition>

